issue.title: single entrypoint docker-compose
issue.body:
- [ ] a slim `Dockerfile` to put the entire build (binary & JS build) into
- [ ] a `docker-compose.yml`, that uses the docker-image and provides a single http-endpoint (potentially with an nginx in front) to
  1. [ ] host and serve the static-html
  2. [ ] allow access to the JSON-RPC 
  3. [ ] pass-through to the websocket

comment.body: That makes sense. But I am thinking of creating two Dockerfiles, one for the binary build and one for the JS frontend build. Having both of them into one image would mean that two process would need to be run in the container (the binary and nginx for serving content).

issue.title: single entrypoint docker-compose
issue.body:
- [ ] a slim `Dockerfile` to put the entire build (binary & JS build) into
- [ ] a `docker-compose.yml`, that uses the docker-image and provides a single http-endpoint (potentially with an nginx in front) to
  1. [ ] host and serve the static-html
  2. [ ] allow access to the JSON-RPC 
  3. [ ] pass-through to the websocket

comment.body:
here is what I currently use at gather.wtf:

Dockerfile:
```Dockerfile
FROM ubuntu:18.04

MAINTAINER "ben@gnunicorn.org"
RUN apt update && apt install -y libssl-dev curl && apt clean
RUN mkdir /gather
WORKDIR /gather
COPY target/release/gather gather
RUN  chmod 770 gather
EXPOSE 9933 9944 30333
VOLUME /gather/local
CMD ./gather --chain=demo -d /gather/local --rpc-external --ws-external --rpc-cors all --validator --name "node-gather-wtf"
```
